erhaps denoting ‘(place) at the huts’ (Old English <i>æt thæm cofum</i> ‘at the huts’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Covan","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Coven  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Coven was born about 1310, in England, United Kingdom. He married Joan De Mourant Apulderfeld about 1340. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1354, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"Abt 1310–Abt 1354":"umbes 1310–umbes 1354","1300–1351":"1300–1351","1335–1354":"1335–1354","1310–1354":"1310–1354","1335":"1335","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","Abt 1354":"umbes 1354","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1351":"1351","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1310–Abt 1354":"noin 1310–noin 1354","1300–1351":"1300–1351","1335–1354":"1335–1354","1310–1354":"1310–1354","1335":"1335","Abt 1310":"noin 1310","Abt 1354":"noin 1354","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","about 1335":"noin 1335","1351":"1351","about 1340":"noin 1340","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Englanti, Yh